   <h2 class="element-invisible">You are here</h2><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> Â» <a href="/programmes" class="active-trail">Programmes</a> Â» Syria</div>   <h1>SITUATION ANALYSIS AND NEEDS</h1>
   <p>The violent conflict in Syria has been escalating in intensity and complexity since March 2011 with devastating humanitarian consequences. Recent estimates suggest over 100,000 have been killed<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="" id="_ftnref1">[1]</a>, 5.1m Syrians are internally displaced<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2" title="" id="_ftnref2">[2]</a> and 2.4m registered refugees in neighbouring countries<a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" title="" id="_ftnref3">[3]</a>. In July 2013 alone, UN DSS recorded 3,414 incidents of armed clashes and heavy weapons use in Syria (see map below). The extensive use of indiscriminate, area-wide weapons is a serious threat to Protection of Civilians, causing both immediate and long-lasting damage. These weapons result in Explosive Remnants of War such as rockets, cluster munitions and IEDs, endangering the lives and livelihoods of generations of Syrians if a rapid and concerted clearance effort is not undertaken in the immediate cessation of conflict.</p>
<div>
<hr /><div>
<p><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="" id="_ftn1">[1]</a> <a href="http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2013/sc11063.doc.htm">http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2013/sc11063.doc.htm</a></p>
</div>
<div>
<p><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" title="" id="_ftn2">[2]</a> <a href="http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/JRANS%20II%20-%20Final%20Report_0.pdf">http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/JRANS%20II%20-%20Final%20Report_0.pdf</a></p>
</div>
<div>
<p><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" title="" id="_ftn3">[3]</a> <a href="http://reliefweb.int/map/syrian-arab-republic/syria-humanitarian-snapshot-15-july-2013-enar">http://reliefweb.int/map/syrian-arab-republic/syria-humanitarian-snapshot-15-july-2013-enar</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<h1>UNMAS PLANNING and READINESS FOR RESPONSE</h1>
<p>With the necessary funding, UNMAS is prepared to instigate risk awareness programmes in Syria, aiming to reach particularly vulnerable groups such as frontline humanitarian aid workers, IDPs and children. UNMAS is currently working with partners in the region to provide coordination for the ERW Risk Education being carried out in Syrian refugee camps in Jordan and Iraq.Â  UNMAS is also seeking funding to further support and expand the Risk Awareness programmes in the bordering regions.</p>
<p>After the cessation of conflict, ERW Survey and Clearance will be vital to enable recovery and reconstruction in Syria. Upon approval from the Syrian Government, UNMAS is uniquely placed to provide the specialized expertise, skills and equipment to respond to explosive hazards. UNMAS currently manages a database of Syria conflict data, in partnership with UNDSS and UN OCHA, to inform the current humanitarian response and enable pre-planning and preparedness for ERW survey and clearance at the appropriate time. As a result, UNMAS will be well-placed to provide holistic and comprehensive coordination to ensure maximum efficiency through appropriate task allocation and prioritization.Â </p>
<h1>CHALLENGES</h1>
<p>The current operating environment in Syria is extremely challenging and the process of approving Government approvals for any activities is lengthy. Furthermore, the security situation is extremely restrictive due to continuous, intense fighting.</p>
<h1>FUNDING REQUIREMENT</h1>
<p>UNMAS is included in the Syrian Humanitarian Assistance Response Plan (SHARP) 2013 with a project that would deliver Risk Awareness to UN and NGO aid workers and initiate a national capacity for delivering Risk Education to vulnerable communities. The amount required for this activity is $801,926 over six months.</p>
<p>Current budget estimates for a rapid and effective humanitarian mine action response in a post-conflict Syria, including vital ERW survey and clearance, is $20m for the first six months. It will be crucial that funds are available for immediate disbursement and activation after the cessation of conflict and therefore donors are requested to consider supporting this through the UNMAS Rapid Response funding mechanism.</p>
<p><em>Updated August 2013</em></p>

